<div class="ru-top-story">
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>MARKETS SLIDE AHEAD OF U.S. JOBS REPORT</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> Markets were <b>cautious on Friday ahead of the latest United States labor market report</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/reuters/2015/09/04/business/04reuters-markets-global.html?ref=international">Reuters reports</a>. Asian markets extended their losses on Friday morning, with the Nikkei 225 closing down 2.15 percent. Chinese markets were closed for a public holiday. European stocks were also down in early trading. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> âOnly one theme is on every traderâs mind today â the <b>United States jobs report tonight</b> and how that may possibly play into the Fedâs September rate decision,â <a href="//uk.reuters.com/article/2015/09/04/uk-markets-global-idUKKCN0R401720150904">said Nicholas Teo</a>, an analyst at the online trading platform provider CMC Markets in Singapore.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> A strong jobs number could ease fears about a global economic slowdown, but it <b>could make it more likely that the Federal Reserve will raise interest rates this month</b>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Mario Draghi, the president of the European Central Bank, pledged on Thursday to increase stimulus spending <b>if the turmoil in the global economy continues</b>, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/09/04/business/international/ecb-leaves-rates-unchanged.html?emc=edit_dlbkpm_20150903&#038;nl=business&#038;nlid=72489293">Jack Ewing reported in The New York Times</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The central bank cut its previous growth forecasts for the eurozone because of global turbulence. Mr. Draghi did note, however, that the E.C.B. <b>would not act until it had more information</b> about the slowdown in emerging markets and other risks. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> âThe Governing Council wanted to emphasize its willingness to act, its readiness to act and its ability to act,â Mr. Draghi said. His remarks <b>buoyed European stocks on Thursday</b>, but the sentiment did not carry over into Friday. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> United States stock futures fell during the Asian day, pointing to a weaker opening on Wall Street after stocks ended slightly higher overnight.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>A THIRD ACT FOR PHILIP FALCONE</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The brash hedge fund titan who managed $26 billion before running afoul of regulators is making his second comeback attempt, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/09/04/business/dealbook/philip-falcone-former-head-of-vast-fundtries-a-3rd-act.html?ref=dealbook">Randall Smith reports in DealBook</a>. Philip A. Falconeâs latest investment platform is <b>a publicly traded company with $800 million in assets</b> called HC2 Holdings.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> It has bought two midsize businesses â an undersea cable installer and a steel fabricator â with the intention of <b>using the cash they generate to support several smaller growth prospects</b> that include operations in wireless services, natural-gas truck-fueling stations, life sciences, insurance and sports. Mr. Falcone wants to hit home runs with the smaller earlier-stage ventures, as he once did by buying bonds of companies in financial distress. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The venture allows him to stay active during a regulatory ban. He is barred from the securities and investment advisory businesses until 2018, but <b>regulators have allowed him to run a public company that buys whole businesses</b> instead of managing a fund trading stocks and bonds.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Mr. Falcone has <b>already had setbacks</b> in his efforts to make a comeback. The results of a larger public-company vehicle he started six years ago were underwhelming.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> HC2âs <b>stock has fallen by 40 percent</b> this summer amid sales by a large investor, after quadrupling in price based on its debt-financed acquisitions. And a $195 million takeover bid that could have doubled HC2âs size was rejected recently.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Mr. Falcone remains undeterred though.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> âIâm a competitor. <b>I think Iâm an unbelievable competitor</b>,â he said. âAs the youngest of nine kids in a three-bedroom house, I learned how not to give up.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Mr. Falcone spent a decade as a high-yield bond trader on Wall Street and then began the <b>Harbinger Capital hedge fund in 2001</b>, focusing on distressed debt. In 2007, he earned $1.7 billion and doubled his investors&#8217; money on a winning bet against subprime mortgages. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> But in 2008, with <b>too many illiquid positions</b>, he faced $10 billion in redemption demands from his investors. Those demands forced him to block investor exits, even as he took a $113 million loan in 2009 to pay his own taxes while also buying out a cofounding partner for about $100 million.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Although Harbinger documents gave him the right to obtain the loan, the Securities and Exchange Commission said in 2013 that he <b>did not form a required fairness committee</b>, did not pay the same rate as Harbinger was paying to borrow and did not disclose the loan to investors for five months.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The S.E.C. inquiry, coupled with losses in 2010 and 2011, eventually <b>doomed the hedge fund</b>. Mr. Falcone insists he will not rush things this time. âIâm looking to build value between now and 10 years from now. It doesnât happen overnight,â he said.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>ON THE AGENDA</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The Labor Department will report the latest data on  <b>hiring and unemployment in August</b>  at<br />
8:30 a.m.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
<div class="ru-story">
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span class="title"><strong>DEFENSE TO REST IN TRIAL OF EX-DEWEY &#038; LEBOEUF EXECUTIVES</strong> <span class="divider"> | </span></span> The lawyers for three former Dewey &#038; LeBoeuf executives on trial accused of using accounting gimmicks to defraud lenders and creditors of the law firm plan to rest their case on Tuesday. They <b>will not have called a single witness to testify</b> in the criminal trial, which began in May, <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/09/04/business/dealbook/defense-to-rest-in-trial-of-3-ex-dewey-leboeuf-leaders.html?ref=dealbook">Matthew Goldstein reports in DealBook</a>. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> The lawyers for Steven H. Davis, the firmâs former chairman; Stephen DiCarmine, the former executive director; and Joel Sanders, the former chief financial officer told Justice Robert M. Stolz of New York State Supreme Court in Manhattan that they <b>intend to proceed directly to closing arguments.</b> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> They are also expected to <b>renew a request to dismiss the case</b>. Prosecutors have indicated they may dismiss some of the criminal charges before the case goes to the jury. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> âThe people havenât proved their case beyond a reasonable doubt,â said Austin Campriello, Mr. DiCarmineâs lawyer. Elkan Abramowitz, the lawyer for Mr. Davis, said it was not always necessary for a defendant to call witnesses <b>âif you can prove your defense through cross-examination.â</b></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> But the decision is surprising given that the prosecution has called more than 40 witnesses during weeks of testimony. The strategy will bolster the defenseâs argument that the prosecutionâs case is <b>based mainly on testimony from cooperating witnesses</b>, who pleaded guilty in hopes of receiving no prison time. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"> Dewey once employed more than 1,200 lawyers around the world and at its peak generated $1 billion in gross revenue annually. But the firm struggled during the financial crisis when merger and acquisition advisory work dried up and it was obligated to pay big salaries to several senior partners. It <b>collapsed in bankruptcy</b> in 2012.</p>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><!-- end .ru-story -->
